description: From Middle English evete, from Old English efeta, of unknown origin.

entries.meaning: A newt, especially the European smooth newt (Lissotriton vulgaris, syn. Triturus punctatus).
examples: How did he like it when the live creatures
Tickled and toused and browsed him all over,
And worm, slug, eft, with serious features
Came in, each one, for his right of trover?

description: From Middle English eft, from Old English eft, æft, from Proto-West Germanic *afti, from Proto-Germanic *aftiz. Compare after, aft.

examples: And when they were all gone, / And the dim moon doth eft withhold the light, […]
